+**Call ordering is load-bearing — the lease-handoff drill MUST run before quiescence, not after.** #147's chaos drill ([its plan §3.3 Phase 5](issue-147-compose-smoke-multi-experiment.md)) kills the lease holder *while work is still in flight*. If the library waited for quiescence first, the orchestrator would already have exited cleanly (it exits 0 when all held leases drain) and there would be **no held leases left to hand off** — the drill would assert against an empty lease table and silently stop testing the failure mode it exists for. The library therefore sequences `me_assert_two_leases → me_lease_handoff_drill → me_wait_quiescence`, and the wrapper examples below follow that order. The drill is responsible for ensuring there is still pending work when it kills the holder (the `MAX_TOTAL=2` cap leaves enough in-flight work that the kill lands before quiescence; if CI proves too fast, the drill gates on observing ≥1 still-`running` experiment before the kill).
